window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You are provided with a stopwatch, a meter rule, a split cork, retort stand and clamp, a pendulum bob, a piece of thread, and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Place the retort stand on a laboratory stool. Clamp the split cork.  (ii) Suspend the pendulum bob from the split cork such that the point of support  P of the bob is at height  H  = 100 cm above the floor  Q . The bob should not touch the floor and  H should be kept constant throughout the experiment.  (iii) Adjust the length of the thread such that the center  A of the bob is at a height y =    AQ =  20 cm from the floor.  (iv) Displace the bob such that it oscillates in a horizontal plane.  (v) Take the time  t for 20 complete oscillations.  (vi) Determine the period  T  of oscillation and evaluate  T2    (vii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of y = 30 cm, 40 cm, 50 cm, and 60 cm. In each case, determine  T  and  T2  .  (viii) Tabulate the results.  (ix) Plot a graph of  T2  on the vertical axis and y on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0).  (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph and the intercept c on the vertical axis.   (xi) If in this experiment  sR = c , calculate  R .  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of value     S/N\ty(cm)\tt(s)\tT(s)\tT2(s2)1 20  35.75  1.788  3.195  2  30 33.40 1.700  2.788 3 40 31.05 1.552 2.409 4 50  28.35 1.418 2.009 5 60\t  25.201.2601.558             (x) s = \u2206T2\u2206y\\frac{\u2206T^{2}}{\u2206y}\u2206y\u2206T2\u200b = T22\u2212T12y2\u2212y1\\frac{T^{2}_{2}-T^{2}_{1}}{y_{2}-y_{1}}y2\u200b\u2212y1\u200bT22\u200b\u2212T12\u200b\u200b = 3.195\u22121.55820\u221260\\frac{3.195-1.558}{20-60}20\u2212603.195\u22121.558\u200b = 1.637\u221240\\frac{1.637}{-40}\u2212401.637\u200b = 0.041 s2cm-1    (xi) Intercept on vertical axis, c = 4 s2    (xii) sR = c    R = cs\\frac{c}{s}sc\u200b = 40.041\\frac{4}{0.041}0.0414\u200b = 97.56 cm     Precautions     1. I avoided parallax error by ensuring my eye level was aligned with the scale while reading the stopwatch, clock, or metre rule to improve accuracy.    2. I checked and corrected for zero error on the stopwatch before taking measurements to ensure precision.    3. I avoided the influence of draughts or air currents by switching off fans and conducting the experiment in a closed environment to maintain stable conditions.    4. I ensured the oscillations were smooth and avoided conical oscillations by carefully adjusting the setup to maintain motion in a single plane.    5. I verified that the support for the apparatus was rigid and firm to prevent vibrations or movements that could affect readings.    6. I ensured repeated readings were taken and averaged to reduce random errors and increase reliability.    7. I performed the experiment in a stable, vibration-free environment to minimize disturbances.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SPEED AND ACCELERATION OF S.H.M","question":"The bob of a simple pendulum is displaced a small distance from the equilibrium position and then released to perform simple harmonic motion Identify where its:  (i) kinetic energy is maximum  (ii) acceleration is maximum","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"(i) The kinetic energy is maximum at the equilibrium position  (ii) The acceleration is maximum at the point of maximum displacement.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION IN STRINGS","question":"An object of weight 120 N vibrates with a period of 4.0 s when hung from a spring. Calculate the force per unit length of the spring. [g = 10m/s2, \u03c0 = 3.142]    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p e.g 123.123 J/s)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The period T is given by    T = 2\u03c0(mk)2\u03c0\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{m}{k}\\right)}2\u03c0(km\u200b)\u200b    T2 = 4\u03c02mk\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}m}{k}k4\u03c02m\u200b    k = 4\u03c02mT2\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}m}{T^{2}}T24\u03c02m\u200b = 4\u00d73.1422\u00d71201042\\frac{4\u00d73.142^{2}\u00d7\\frac{120}{10}}{4^{2}}424\u00d73.1422\u00d710120\u200b\u200b = 29.62 N/m","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a converging lens and holder, a screen, a ray box containing an illuminated object pin, and a meter rule.    (i) Place the lens in its holder such that it is facing a distant object seen through a well-lit laboratory window. Move the screen to and fro until a sharp image of the distant object is formed on it. Measure the distance,  fo , between the screen and the lens.  (ii) Clamp the meter rule securely to the table. Place the illuminated object pin at the end  R  of the meter rule.   (iii) Place the lens at a position  P such that  X = RP  = 20 cm.  (iv) Move the screen to a position  Q  to receive a sharp image of the object. Measure the distance  Y = PQ.   (v) Evaluate  Z = (X + Y)   (vi) Repeat the procedure for five other values of  x  = 25 cm, 30 cm, 35 cm, 40 cm and 45 cm. In each case, record  X, Y  and evaluate  Z .   (vii) Tabulate the results.  (viii) Plot a graph with  Z  on the vertical axis and  X  on the horizontal axis. Draw a smooth curve through the points.  (ix) Determine from your graph the minimum value of Z = Z 0 and its corresponding distance X0.  (x) Evaluate W = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b (Z04\\frac{Z_{0}}{4}4Z0\u200b\u200b + X02\\frac{X_{0}}{2}2X0\u200b\u200b)  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"fo =15.2 cm    Table of Value    S/N\tX(cm)Y(cm)\tZ = (X + Y) (cm)1    20  68.5    88.5   2 25       43.3    68.3    3   30      33.0    63.0     4      35     28.5  63.5     5      40            24.3       64.3      6          45            23.7   68.7        (ix) Minimum value of Z = Z 0 from the graph = 60.8 cm    Corresponding distance of X 0 = 35.5 cm    (x) W = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b (Z04\\frac{Z_{0}}{4}4Z0\u200b\u200b + X02\\frac{X_{0}}{2}2X0\u200b\u200b) = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b (60.84\\frac{60.8}{4}460.8\u200b + 35.52\\frac{35.5}{2}235.5\u200b) = 16.5 cm     Precautions     1. I carefully arranged the optical instruments, ensuring the ray box, lens, and screen were aligned along a straight line to maintain a coaxial setup and ensure precise light convergence.    2. I avoided parallax errors by positioning my eye level directly in line with the scale on the metre rule while taking measurements.    3. I made sure the lens was kept upright and firmly positioned to prevent it from tilting or displacing during the experiment.    4. I thoroughly cleaned the lens surface before use, removing any dust, smudges, or fingerprints to enhance the clarity of the image and avoid scattered light.    5. I took repeated readings, documented them in a table, and averaged them to improve accuracy and reliability.    6. I adjusted the ray box carefully to produce a uniform beam of light, ensuring it was positioned at the correct distance from the lens for clear image formation.    7. I performed the experiment in a dimly lit environment to minimize interference from external light sources, which could distort the image on the screen.    8. I handled all instruments gently, regularly checking the alignment during the experiment to avoid unintended shifts that could compromise the setup.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Draw a ray diagram to show how a convex lens forms an image of magnification less than one.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"Name two pairs of features in the human eye and a lens camera that performs similar functions.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are several pairs of features in the human eye and a lens camera that perform similar functions:    1. Lens and Focusing Mechanism:    The lens in the human eye adjusts its shape (accommodation) to focus light on the retina, similar to how the lens in a camera adjusts its position or curvature to focus light on the film or sensor.    2. Retina and Camera Sensor/Film:    The retina captures the image as light-sensitive cells convert light into neural signals, just as the sensor or film in a camera records the image as electrical signals or a developed photo.    3. Iris and Aperture:    The iris controls the amount of light entering the eye by adjusting the pupil's size, just as the aperture in a camera adjusts to control the light entering the lens.    4. Cornea and Protective Lens Cover:    The cornea is the transparent, curved surface at the front of the eye that helps focus incoming light, similar to a protective lens cover in a camera.    5. Pupil and Diaphragm Opening:    The pupil regulates light entry by dilating or constricting, just as the diaphragm opening in a camera adjusts to allow the correct amount of light for proper exposure.    6. Optic Nerve and Digital Output/Wiring:    The optic nerve transmits visual information from the retina to the brain for processing, similar to how a camera's wiring or output transmits data to a display or storage device.    7. Vitreous Humor and Camera Body Interior:    The vitreous humor, a clear gel, maintains the eye's shape and ensures light reaches the retina unobstructed, akin to the camera body's interior, which protects components and supports functionality.    These parallels highlight how biological and mechanical systems have evolved to perform similar image-capturing functions.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with a battery of e.m.f.  E , a key  K , a voltmeter, a standard resistor  Ro  = 2 \u03a9, a resistance box R, and some connecting wires.    (i) Measure and record the e.m.f.  E of the battery.  (ii) Set up a circuit as shown in the diagram above with the key open.   (iii) Set the resistance on the resistance box to  R  = 2 \u03a9.  (iv) Close the key, read and record the potential difference  V  on the voltmeter.  (v) Evaluate V -1  (vi) Repeat the procedures for five other values of  R  = 5 \u03a9, 10 \u03a9, 12 \u03a9, 15 \u03a9 and 20 \u03a9. In each case, record  V and evaluate  V-1 \t   (vii) Tabulate the results.  (viii) Plot a graph with  R  on the vertical axis and  V-1  on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0).  (ix) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph and the intercept c on the vertical axis.  (x) Calculate  \u03b1 and \u03b2  from the equations  s  =  R0\u03b1   and  c  = -(R0 + \u03b2).  (xi) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"E = 3.0 V    Table of value    S/N\tR(\u03a9)V(V)V-1(V-1)1 2 1.02 0.9812 5 0.73 1.3703 10 0.442.2734 12 0.372.7035 15  0.313.2266\t20  0.20 5.000        (ix)   s = \u2206R\u2206V\u22121\\frac{\u2206R}{\u2206V^{-1}}\u2206V\u22121\u2206R\u200b = R2\u2212R1V2\u22121\u2212V1\u22121\\frac{R_{2}-R_{1}}{V^{-1}_{2}-V^{-1}_{1}}V2\u22121\u200b\u2212V1\u22121\u200bR2\u200b\u2212R1\u200b\u200b = 18.5\u221274.375\u22121.75\\frac{18.5-7}{4.375-1.75}4.375\u22121.7518.5\u22127\u200b = 11.52.625\\frac{11.5}{2.625}2.62511.5\u200b = 4.38 \u03a9V    Intercept on the vertical axis, c:    To get the equation of the line (y = mx + c):    y - 18.5 = 4.38(x - 4.375)    y - 18.5 = 4.38x - 19.163    y = 4.38x - 0.663    \u2234 c = -0.663 \u03a9    (x)   1.  s  =  R0\u03b1      \u03b1 = sR0\\frac{s}{R_{0}}R0\u200bs\u200b = 4.382\\frac{4.38}{2}24.38\u200b = 2.19 V    2.  c  = -(R0 + \u03b2)    -0.663 = -(2 + \u03b2)    0.663 = 2 + \u03b2    \u03b2 = -1.34 \u03a9     Precautions     1. I ensured the key was opened between readings or whenever readings were not being taken to prevent the cells from running down.    2. I checked and maintained tight connections throughout the setup to ensure consistent current flow and avoid potential measurement errors.    3. I took repeated readings and documented them systematically in a table to improve accuracy and reliability.    4. I cleaned all terminal connections thoroughly before use to minimize contact resistance and enhance conductivity.    5. I avoided parallax errors by aligning my line of sight properly with the scales on measuring instruments such as the voltmeter and ammeter.    6. I ensured the setup was stable and free from vibrations to prevent fluctuations in readings.    7. I double-checked the calibration of all instruments and corrected any zero errors before starting the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"In the circuit diagram above, the battery has negligible internal resistance. Calculate the power dissipated as heat in the section AB of the circuit.    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"VAB = 12 - 8 = 4 V    RAB = 4\u00d754+5\\frac{4\u00d75}{4+5}4+54\u00d75\u200b = 209\\frac{20}{9}920\u200b    PAB = VAB2RAB\\frac{V^{2}_{AB}}{R_{AB}}RAB\u200bVAB2\u200b\u200b = 42\u00d7920\\frac{4^{2}\u00d79}{20}2042\u00d79\u200b = 7.2 W","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2019>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2019","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"An electric equipment of power rating 3.6 kW is to be connected to a 240 V line whose circuit breaker is rated 20 A. Justify whether or not the breaker would open when the equipment is switched on.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"To determine whether the breaker will open, we calculate the current drawn by the equipment and compare it to the circuit breaker's rating.    I = PV\\frac{P}{V}VP\u200b = 3.6\u00d7103240\\frac{3.6\u00d710^{3}}{240}2403.6\u00d7103\u200b = 15 A    The current drawn, 15 A, is less than the breaker's rated capacity of 20 A.    Conclusion:  The breaker will not open when the equipment is switched on, as the current drawn by the device is well within the breaker's capacity. However, if additional devices are connected to the same circuit, the combined current might exceed the breaker's rating, causing it to trip.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];